The Enabling Act of 1933, also known as the "Law to Remedy the Distress of the People and the Reich," was passed on March 23, 1933, with 441 votes in favor and 94 votes against. The First Chamber of the Reichstag, which was the German parliament at the time, had a total of 647 members. Therefore, approximately 68% of the members of the First Chamber voted in favor of the Enabling Act.

It's worth noting that the Enabling Act was a crucial piece of legislation that allowed Adolf Hitler and the Nazi Party to consolidate power and effectively establish a dictatorship in Germany. The act gave the government the authority to pass laws without the approval of the Reichstag, which effectively eliminated the checks and balances of the German political system.
